<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>Madeleine McCann suspect Christian Brueckner has given a rare insight into his life behind bars by drawing a pencil sketch of his cramped prison cell.</p>

<p>The drawing has emerged as police continue to investigate his role in the three-year-old's disappearance in Portugal in 2007.</p>

<p>Brueckner complains that he suffers from being unable to exercise properly as he has been confined to solitary for his own protection since June – when German police named him as the prime suspect in the case.</p>

<p>The 43-year-old's only daily contact is with prison warders and the inmate who dishes out his meals. His lawyer Freidrich Fulcher is his only visitor.</p>

<p>Madeleine McCann suspect Christian Brueckner has given a rare insight into his life behind bars by drawing a pencil sketch of his cramped prison cell</p>

<p>Brueckner spends 23 hours a day in the cramped cell in the Kiel high security prison in northern Germany, where he serving a three-year-sentence for drug dealing.</p>

<p>A seven-year conviction for the rape of an American pensioner in Portugal has still to be confirmed.</p>

<p>His living space measures three-metre long and has 60cm open area between his bed and his desk. There is a shelf on the wall, where he stores legal files about his case in folders.</p>

<p>There is a sink and a toilet behind a curtain. All the furniture is screwed in to the floor, except the chair.</p>

<p>He also has his own television, from where he keeps abreast of the latest developments in the Madeleine McCann case, it has been reported.</p>

<p>His meals include stew on Mondays, fish on Thursdays and a roast dinner on Sundays.</p>

<p> Brueckner complains that he suffers from being unable to exercise properly as he has been confined to solitary for his own protection since June – when German police named him as the prime suspect in the case</p>

<p>Brueckner spends his time making drawings – a pastime he shares with the fictional character Hannibal Lecter, the mass murderer from the film 'Silence of the Lambs', Germany's Bild newspaper claims.</p>

<p>'He has made paintings and hung them in his cell,' the paper reported.</p>

<p>'Until June 2020, Christian B. was an inmate like everyone in the prison in Kiel. [But] He has been separated from the other inmates since it was revealed he was involved in the Maddie case. Now [Brueckner] sits in his solitary cell 23 hours a day.</p>

<p>'He has an hour of courtyard exercise every day – alone. A protective measure, as a suspected child killer, Christian B. was harassed by other inmates.</p>

<p>'[Brueckner] only has contact with warders and the inmate who distributes the food.'</p>

<p>The newspaper continued: 'In his cell, the child abuser has a television, thus informing himself about the progress of the [Madeleine McCann] investigation].</p>

<p>Madeleine McCann went missing while on holiday in Portugal with her family in May 2007</p>

<p>'He [Brueckner] draws a lot. And he complains about circulatory disorders because he can move so little. The furniture in the cell is screwed in the floor, he has barely three-metres square of space for exercise.'</p>

<p>Brueckner has made three applications for more exercise time to prison authorities but all have been refused.</p>

<p>The German drifter lived in a ramshackle cottage just 15-minutes-drive from the holiday apartment in Praia da Luz, Algarve, from where Madeleine McCann went missing in May 2007.</p>

<p>Mobile phone evidence places Brueckner in the tourist village on the night the youngster disappeared and he has been linked with a series of 25 break-ins throughout the resort.</p>

<p>Brueckner has been convicted for a string of sex crimes, including the sexual assault of children.</p>

<p>Friedrich Fulcher, his lawyer, maintains his client is innocent.</p>
